[normal]Background to my re[bold]search on human prion diseases [bold]that is relevant to the questions [bold]that[bold] I have been invited to [bold]respond[bold] to for this Evidence Session[bold]. [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]I am Professor of Clinical Neuropathology in the University of Edinburgh and Honorary Consultant Neuropathologist in NHS Lothian Hospitals Division. I have worked in the 
[normal]UK 
[normal]National CJD 
[normal]Surveillance Unit (now renamed as 
[normal]t
[normal]he National CJD Research &amp; Surveillance Unit (NCJDRSU)) since it was established by the Department of Health in 1990 in the University of Edinburgh. The key aim
[normal]s
[normal] of NCJDRSU 
[normal]are
[normal] to 
[normal]monitor the characteristics of all forms of CJD, to identify trends in incidence rates, to study risk factors for the development of disease and to contribute to improving the quality of care for those with CJD
[normal] (
[normal]www.cjd.ed.ac.uk
[normal])
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In 1996, my colleagues and I identified a new form of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD) that 
[normal]is known as variant CJD (vCJD)
[normal] (28
[normal])
[normal], and in collaboration with other researchers we demonstrated that the infectious agent or prion causing vCJD (but not 
[normal]sporadic CJD (sCJD), the commonest form of CJD
[normal]) closely resembled the prion causing bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE)
[normal] in its biochemical profile on Western blot assay 
[normal](5) 
[normal]and on experimental transmission in a strain typing assay
[normal] (3)
[normal]. On the basis of this finding, vCJD is often referred to as “the human form of BSE”. Since then, my colleagues and I have monitored the incidence of vCJD in the UK and studied in detail the clinical and neuropathological features of the disease
[normal] (11,16)
[normal]. We also undertook 
[normal]epidemiological studies and 
[normal]a case control study (funded by DH)
[normal] (27
[normal])
[normal] to identify risk factors for vCJD, and produced a set of 
[normal]diagnostic criteria that was accepted by the World Health Organisation (WHO)
[normal] (30
[normal])
[normal]; NCJDRSU is now both a national and international referral centre for cases of suspected vCJD. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The NCJDRSU 
[normal]website (
[normal]www.cjd.ed.ac.uk
[normal]) 
[normal]gives updated information on all forms of CJD in the UK and has figures for all the vCJD cases in the UK
[normal] (current total 177 cases)
[normal], including data on the incidence and death rates from this disease
[normal], both of which show a decline in recent years
[normal]. 
[normal]Most cases of vCJD occur in young adults with a median age at death of 28 years; the age at death has not changed greatly 
[normal]over time
[normal]. Only 5 cases of vCJD have been identified in patients aged 60 years and over. 
[normal]All definite cases of vCJD (that have been confirmed pathologically) belong to a genetic subgroup of the population defined by a 
[normal]naturally occurring
[normal] polymorphism at codon 129 in the open reading frame of the prion protein gene 
[normal](
[normal]PRNP
[normal]) 
[normal]on chromosome 22. Either methionine (M) or valine (V) can be encoded, resulting in 3 possible genotypes: MM, MV and VV
[normal] (Table 1)
[normal]. All definite vCJD cases possess the MM genotype. There is evidence that the MV and VV genotypes 
[normal]are 
[normal]be susceptible to vCJD infection 
[normal](2,8,17,
[normal]22
[normal]) 
[normal]and  as this polymorphism is known to influence the incubation period of other acquired human prion diseases, e.g. kuru
[normal] (6
[normal],
[normal]19
[normal])
[normal], it is possible that vCJD cases may yet emerge in these genotypes in the future.
[normal]&#xa0;
